################################################################################
# Git LFS configuration for vendored Tauri Sidecars
#
# This file tells Git to use LFS (Large File Storage) for the heavy binary
# files and modules downloaded by the sidecar vendoring script. This keeps the
# main repository history small and fast.
################################################################################

# --- Rule Definitions ---

# 1. Track the main Node.js executables with LFS.
#    - 'node.exe' for Windows
#    - 'node' for Linux and macOS
**/NODE/**/node.exe filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs
**/NODE/**/bin/node filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs

# 2. Track the entire contents of the vendored npm and corepack modules.
#    While they contain many small JS files, treating the entire module as an
#    LFS object is clean and prevents thousands of small files from bloating
#    the Git history every time you update a Node version.
#    This covers both the `lib/node_modules` (Linux/macOS) and `node_modules` (Windows) layouts.
**/NODE/**/node_modules/npm/** filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs
**/NODE/**/lib/node_modules/npm/** filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs

**/NODE/**/node_modules/corepack/** filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs
**/NODE/**/lib/node_modules/corepack/** filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs

# --- Files NOT tracked by LFS (Implicitly) ---
#
# The following files are small and will be handled by standard Git:
# - The wrapper scripts: `npm`, `npx`, `corepack` (in `bin/` or the root)
# - The Windows command scripts: `npm.cmd`, `npx.cmd`, `corepack.cmd`
